return clause info with null `OperationInfo` when targeting netcoreapp3.0.

Affects test `StatementEditingTests.Queries_Update_Signature_Join4`.

The cannonical way to use the `CallerMemberName` attribute is by assigning null as a default value to it, like so:
```C#
public void M([CallerMemberName] string param = null) {
}
```
But this will produce a warning, because param is declared as having a default value of null, even though the `null` won't ever actually be used. We should try and support the existing way people write this code, without requiring them to suppress the null.

This results in incorrect EnC analysis, which may now allow edits that corrupt the debuggee.

Repro:

```C#
using System;
using System.Linq;

class C
{
	int Z(Func<int> f)
	{
		return 1;
	}

    void F()
    {
		var result = from a in new[] { 1 }
		             from b in new[] { 2 }
		             where Z(() => a + b) > 0
		             select a;
    }
}
```

The result of `SemanticModel.AnalyzeDataFlow(body).Captured` for function `F` is 
- {`this`, `a`, `b` } when targeting net46
- {`this`} when targeting netcoreapp3.0

