When commenting other lines in a `.tsx` file, vim-commentary uses `commentstring` for any selection, leading to things like:

```ts

{/* const myUtility = () => { */}
{/*   return 'something' */}
{/* } */}

export const MyComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* <p>Hello</p> */}
      <p>World</p>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Is there a way to get this to apply only to JSX?

In the meantime, a workaround is just setting the `commentstring` back to its default in your .vimrc:

```
autocmd FileType typescript.tsx setlocal commentstring=//\ %s
```

(this means that commenting JSX won't work, though)

This PR is based on expert feedback. 
Objects like this:
```
let obj = {
  foo: function() {...}
};
```
can be simplified to:
```
let obj = {
  foo() {...}
};
```
This was done for all methods in the generated Vue code.

@daotyl000 and @nchowder should begin writing our research paper in this private Google Doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MB4GjzjU6bX8OkneXVCYoiCPL44bLBEZ1YTSxS7Wsdc/edit.
We will want the following structure:
- Abstract - Intro -- 5-7 paragraphs where first para describes problem, second para describes prior work addressing problem, third para introduces our solution, fourth para introduces our method/evaluation, fifth para describes our findings, and sixth paragraph enumerates our research contributions - Related Work -- Should have three sub-sections where each sub-section captures a broad span of literature related to our work. For example, one sub-section could be on general background on Crowdsourcing systems and Citizen Science. A second sub-section could be specifically on quality control solutions. A third sub-section could focus purely on implicitly inferring user quality based on interactions (as we're doing here) - Experiments and Findings -- Should enumerate all of our little experiments and investigations + findings - Discussion -- Should discuss open issues, limitations, future work, etc.

