This is a follow-up to #35667.

See https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/35667#issuecomment-507758934.

### Sample code

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// <code>
/// code line 1
/// code line 2
/// </code>
/// </summary>
private int value;
```

### Expected result

Quick Info for `value` renders the summary code as a two-line code block with code font.

### Actual result

Quick Info for `value` renders the summary code on one line with code font.

**Example**
```
class C
{
	private string _a;
	private string _bb;
	private string _cccc;

	void M()
	{
		_a    = "a";
		_bb   = "b";
		_cccc = "c";
	}
}
```

**Problem**
`csharp_space_around_binary_operators` also affects assignments.
This is not always desirable. The example above should not be reformatted.
There is currently no way to enforce `csharp_space_around_binary_operators` and
ignore spaces in assignments.

**Proposal**
Handle the assignment operator (=) with a new rule:
`csharp_space_around_assignments = [before_and_after|ignore]`

Tagging: @sharwell

**Version Used**: vs 16.3 preview 1.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;

public class C {
    int? a = null;
    public int M() {
        Release.Assert(a != null);
        return a.Value;
    }
}

internal static class Release
{
	public static void Assert([DoesNotReturnIf(false)] bool condition)
	{
		if (!condition)
			Environment.FailFast();
	}
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
No warning

**Actual Behavior**:
CS8629: Nullable value type may be null

```cs
class C
{
    void M(object? o1)
    {
        foreach ((var o2, object o3) in new[] { (o1, o1) })
        { 
            o3.ToString();
        }
    }
}
```

The call to `o3.ToString()` should warn, and there should be a warning on converting a nullable reference type to a non-nullable reference type in the assignment to o3.

