**Actual Behavior**:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5644458/61632657-f4f5ef00-acbf-11e9-8d86-6ca98f91d138.png)

I'm trying to replicate some light Option\<T> on C#8, but I'm getting an error in the switch expression

Consider the code:
```cs
   public abstract class Option<T> { }
   public class None<T> : Option<T> { }
   public class Some<T> : Option<T> {
       public T Value { get; }
       public Some(T value) => Value = value;
   }
```
If i try property pattern on Some\<T> the compiler throws a syntax error

```cs
static string Match(Option<Foo> maybeFoo) =>
    maybeFoo switch
    {
        // works
        None<Foo> _ => "Theres nothing",

        // works
        Some<Foo> someFoo when someFoo.Value.Bar > 42 => someFoo.Value.Baz,

        // Syntax error
        Some<Foo> { Value: var p } when p.Bar == 42 => p.Baz,

        _ => string.Empty,
    };

```
If I define a Type alias to Some\<Foo> it works as expected

```cs
using SomeFoo = Program.Some<Foo>;

static string Match(Option<Foo> maybeFoo) =>
    maybeFoo switch
    {
        // works
        None<Foo> _ => "Theres nothing",

        // now works
        SomeFoo { Value: var p } when p.Bar == 42 => p.Baz,

        _ => string.Empty,
    };
```

**Version Used**: 16.2.0-preview-19278-01+d635043bd

**Steps to Reproduce**:
```
mkdir NullableTest && cd NullableTest
dotnet new console
```
Then enable NullableContextOptions, and write code:
```csharp
using System;

namespace NullableTest
{
    class InnerClass
    {
        public bool TestField;
    }
    class Test
    {
        public InnerClass? InnerField;
    }
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
        }

        static bool Test()
        {
            var x = new Test();
            if (x.InnerField?.TestField ?? false) // obviously if x.InnerField is null, it won't enter the `if` statement so there's no nullable-related issues
            {
                return x.InnerField.TestField;
            }
            return false;
        }
    }
}
```

```
dotnet build
```

**Expected Behavior**:
No warnings and no errors.

**Actual Behavior**:
```
Program.cs(25,24): warning CS8602: Dereference of a possibly null reference.
```

**Additional Information**
The if (xx?.yy ?? false) is commonly used in C#, I hope that Roslyn can support checking nullability for this syntax

When writing a multi-line variable assignment such as the following, VS will, by default, indent the second line of the assignment one level:

```csharp
var nonemptyStrings =
    SomeVeryLongExpression();
```

That is, if I type `var nonemptyStrings =` and press enter, my cursor is positioned on the following line with indentation preapplied. I do not have to take any action beyond typing the body of the expression to get the correct indentation.

However, when writing the same code inside of a lambda, Visual Studio uses different indentation. In fact, it will not indent at all for this situation. If I type `var nonemptyStrings = ` and press enter inside of a lambda, my cursor is set on the next line at the same position as the `v` in `var`. For example, consider these keyboard inputs where I type the value verbatim and press ENTER for each bullet:
* `FuncUtil.Invoke(()=&gt;{`
* `var things=`
* `&quot;&quot;.Length;`
* `return things;});`

Actual: the code I get from the above keyboard inputs is:

```csharp
FuncUtil.Invoke(() =>
{
    var things =
    "".Length;
    return things;
});
```

Expected: my expected code is:

```csharp
FuncUtil.Invoke(() =>
{
    var things =
        "".Length;
    return things;
});
```

It seems like the indentation controller thing is quite different inside of lambdas compared to outside of them. This makes it difficult and time consuming to write readable code which utilizes lambdas.

I rely on the multi-line assignment and indentation for writing LINQ Query expressions because that, IMO, makes them the most readable.

